# Power Chess - Global Rules

## Product Context
- 1v1 multiplayer chess game with card-based powers.
- Core chess movement and check/checkmate logic must be preserved.
- Never allow an instant checkmate caused directly by a power.

## Source of Truth
- Treat `PROJECT.md` as the primary business-rules reference.
- In ambiguous cases, prioritize gameplay consistency and backend validation.

## Backend (Go)
- Keep authoritative game rules on the server.
- WebSocket events are the source of truth for turn, mana, strikes, ignition, and cooldown state.
- Write clear, testable code with explicit naming and small functions.
- Design the power/ability system for extensibility (new cards and effects without refactoring core turn logic).
- Prefer effect-based architecture (card definition + resolver + validation pipeline) over hard-coded per-card branching in many places.

## Database and Persistence
- Use PostgreSQL as the primary database.
- Use GORM as the default ORM for Go services.
- Use `golang-migrate` for versioned SQL migrations.
- Run migrations automatically during service startup (safe, idempotent) and in containerized environments.
- Initial table design is flexible and should be defined when implementation begins.

## Frontend (HTML/CSS/JS)
- Keep the HUD simple and readable.
- Do not duplicate critical game-rule authority in the client.
- Client-side validation can improve UX, but final decisions belong to the backend.

## Code Standards
- Prefer single-responsibility functions and small modules.
- Avoid coupling business rules to presentation layers.
- Add comments only for non-obvious logic.
- Default to ASCII in source files unless there is a clear reason not to.

## Delivery Discipline
- Document rule changes in `PROJECT.md` when they affect gameplay.
- Update `README.md` when setup, tooling, or run instructions change.
- Always create tests for each new functionality and bug fix.
- Only commit when tests are passing (expected 100% pass rate for the relevant suite in CI/local runs).
